A name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="ncat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Content Types</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nrvw"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfact"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Factiva Filters</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nrvw"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfce"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nrvw"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipd">The Arts/Cultural Desk Review </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">The Arts/Cultural Desk; SECTC</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Fever Dream Of a Play Shifts Shape</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>In the middle of the forest, in the middle of the play, quite a distance down a narrative path littered with hairpin turns, one unnamed character asks another a clarifying question: ''Aren't you the murderer?''</Para><Para>''I was never the murderer,'' the possible murderer (Samuel Im) replies, though he understands any confusion on that point. ''They call me that,'' he explains. ''Sort of a nickname.''</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Sort of. I, for one, had been thinking of him as the murderer ever since the darkly comic opening scene of ''Distant Observer: Tokyo/New York Correspondence,'' where he blurts out a confession of his homicidal past and his 10 years' time served. I kept thinking of him as the murderer even when it emerged that his supposed victim had actually killed herself, and he lied to protect her from shame. Or then again maybe she was murdered after all, just not by him, and by the way, what is he doing with that very long and bloody knife?</Para><Para>In the mesmeric, deadpan fever dream of a play that is ''Distant Observer,'' at La MaMa, you grasp onto what you can in trying to keep track of who's who, and what's occurring. Like Surrealists playing an extended game of Exquisite Corpse, the play's authors -- Takeshi Kawamura, in Japan, and John Jesurun, in the United States -- tossed the script back and forth for three years, translation facilitating their exchange. With Mr. Kawamura working in Japanese, Mr. Jesurun in English, each new section one of them wrote was in response to the previous section by the other. Inside the world they built, reality and identity are mutable things, place and memory ephemeral, truth elusive. Plot, too.</Para><Para>Written in English and Japanese, directed by Mr. Jesurun (who is also responsible for the striking video and set design) and performed in English by a nimble cast of five, the play is woolly and protean but verbally seamless; Mr. Kawamura's contributions, translated by Aya Ogawa, are indistinguishable from Mr. Jesurun's. Though there are times you might want to bet who wrote what -- as when a woman (Kotoba Dan) suggests splurging on a vacation to ''Manila or California.''</Para><Para>''They all have guns there,'' another woman (Claire Buckingham) replies. ''I wouldn't feel safe.''</Para><Para>Political concerns surface now and again, but mortality is the theme that asserts itself most strongly, especially when the perplexing action moves to the forest -- a stand-in for Japan's so-called Suicide Forest. Even then, though, the heightened tone of the performance keeps it from feeling grim.</Para><Para>So does the humor. When the piece starts commenting on itself (''I'm not even a character, I'm just like some kind of idea floating around,'' someone says), it's actually pretty charming. There's a playful, volleying spirit to the whole endeavor -- intriguing, endearing and odd.</Para><Para>Distant Observer: Tokyo/New York Correspondence</Para><Para>Through April 1 at La MaMa, Manhattan; 866-811-4111, lamama.org. Running time: 1 hour 10 minutes.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By LAURA COLLINS-HUGHES </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">From left, Kyle Griffiths, Claire Buckingham and Samuel Im in ''Distant Observer: Tokyo/New York Correspondence,'' at La MaMa. (PHOTOGRAPH BY PAULA COURT) </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

